# See https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/builder/#dockerignore-file.
#
# Applied to every image — all share the repo-root build context: gmc, agc,
# proxy, fakegithub, worker (see docker-bake.hcl, where _common sets
# context = ".").
#
# Strategy: exclude everything, re-include only the Go source and module
# manifests builds actually need. This keeps the layer-cache key tight —
# changes to docs, scripts, the .build directory, tools/, etc. do not
# invalidate `COPY . .` and force a Go rebuild.

# Default-deny.
**

# Go source — but never tests, which are not needed at runtime and would
# bloat the build context.
!**/*.go
**/*_test.go

# Module / workspace manifests at every level.
!go.mod
!go.sum
!go.work
!go.work.sum
!**/go.mod
!**/go.sum

# Workspace vendor tree at the repo root — produced by `go work vendor` and
# consumed by every Dockerfile via auto-detected `-mod=vendor`.
!vendor/**

# Re-exclude the tools vendor tree. Tools (controller-gen, kubebuilder, etc.)
# are built only for `make tools`, never for runtime images — without this
# re-exclude the !**/*.go rule above pulls its ~29 MB of source back in.
tools/vendor/**

# License attribution bundled into every production image at /licenses/
# (Apache-2.0 §4(d), the MIT/BSD reproduce-the-notice clauses). THIRD-PARTY-NOTICES
# is generated from vendor/ by `make third-party-notices`. Each production
# Dockerfile COPYs these three files; without the re-include the default-deny
# `**` above hides them from the build context and the COPY fails.
!LICENSE
!NOTICE
!THIRD-PARTY-NOTICES

# If a build ever needs a non-.go file (an embedded asset, a config
# template, etc.) re-include the specific path here. Do not blanket-include
# directories — the point of this file is to keep the context tight.
